08512nam a22010815i 9783110314694DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979745565  a97831103146947 a10.1515/97831103146942doi  a(DE-B1597)208988  a(OCoLC)890070959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0062202bisacsh00aMark and Paul :bComparative Essays Part II. For and Against Pauline Influence on Mark /ced. by Eve-Marie Becker, Troels Engberg-Pedersen, Mogens Mueller. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (330 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBeihefte zur Zeitschrift für die neutestamentliche Wissenschaft ,x0171-6441 ;v19900tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of Contents -- tMark and Paul – Introductory Remarks -- tI. Histories and Contexts -- tMark as Allegorical Rewriting of Paul: Gustav Volkmar’s Understanding of the Gospel of Mark -- tMark – Interpreter of Paul -- tPaul and Mark – Mark and Paul A Critical Outline of the History of Research -- t“Evangelium” im Markusevangelium Zum traditionsgeschichtlichen Ort des ältesten Evangeliums -- tEarliest Christian literary activity: Investigating Authors, Genres and Audiences in Paul and Mark -- tIn the Beginning was the Congregation In Search of a Tertium Comparationis between Paul and Mark -- tII. Texts and Interpretations -- tRomans 1:1–7 and Mark 1:1–3 in Comparison Two Opening Texts at the Beginning of Early Christian Literature -- tMan and the Son of Man in Mark 2:27–28 An Exegesis of Mark 2:23–28 Focussing on the Christological Discourse in Mark 2:27–28 with an Epilogue Concerning Pauline Parallels -- tMark 7:1–23: A Pauline Halakah? -- tPaul in Mark 8:34–9:1: Mark on what it is to be a Christian -- tIII. Topics and Perspectives -- tThe Politics of Beginnings – Cosmology, Christology and Covenant: Gospel Openings Reconsidered in the Light of Paul’s Pneumatology -- tAdam-Christ Typology in Paul and Mark: Reflections on a Tertium Comparationis -- tThe Cross on the Way to Mark -- tPersecution and Denial – Paradigmatic Apostolic Portrayals in Paul and Mark -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Subjects and Names -- tIndex of References0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume brings together an international group of scholars on Mark and Paul, respectively, who reopen the question whether Paul was a direct influence on Mark. On the basis of the latest methods in New Testament scholarship, the battle over Yes and No to this question of literary and theological influence is waged within these pages. In the end, no agreement is reached, but the basic issues stand out with much greater clarity than before. How may one relate two rather different literary genres, the apostolic letter and the narrative gospel? How may the theologies of two such different types of writing be compared? Are there sufficient indications that Paul lies directly behind Mark for us to conclude that through Paul himself and Mark the New Testament as a whole reflects specifically Pauline ideas? What would the literary and theological consequences of either assuming or denying a direct influence be for our reconstruction of 1st century Christianity? And what would the consequences be for either understanding Mark or Paul as literary authors and theologians? How far should we give Paul an exalted a position in the literary creativity of the first Christians? Addressing these questions are scholars who have already written seminally on the issue or have marked positions on it, like Joel Marcus, Margaret Mitchell, Gerd Theissen and Oda Wischmeyer, together with a group of up-coming and senior Danish scholars from Aarhus and Copenhagen Universities who have collaborated on the issue for some years. The present volume leads the discussion further that has been taken up in: “Paul and Mark” (ed. by O. Wischmeyer, D. Sim, and I. Elmer), BZNW 191, 2013.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aEvangelien. 4aIntertextualität. 4aMarkusevangelium. 4aNeues Testament. 4aPaulus. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / New Testament.2bisacsh  aNew Testament.  aintertextuality.  aliterary and theological influence.1 aBecker, Eve-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Eve-Marie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBro Larsen, Kasper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuch-Hansen, Gitte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamgaard, Finn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidsen, Ole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDochhorn, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngberg-Pedersen, Troels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngberg-Pedersen, Troels, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMarcus, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMueller, Mogens, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMüller, Mogens, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNielsen, Jesper Tang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOmerzu, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTheissen, Gerd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVig Skoven, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWischmeyer, Oda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gru